Sub-Saharan African Stocks Report: Crown Berger, Rogers, Total Kenya Move

-- B y   S t e p h e n   G u n n i o n
-- 
2011-08-25T16:40:06Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-25/sub-saharan-african-stocks-report-rogers-total-kenya-move.html
Kenya ’s All-Share Index fell to a
19-month low, declining 2 percent to 60.96 by the 3 p.m. close
in Nairobi.  Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index advanced for a third day, rising
0.2 percent to 1,944.68 by the 1:30 p.m. close in  Port Louis .  The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index declined for a
fifth day, dropping 1.1 percent to 22,061.21 by the 2:30 p.m.
close in Lagos, according to an e-mailed statement from the
bourse.  Namibia ’s FTSE/ Namibia Overall Index (FTN098)  fell 0.5 percent to
752.00 by the 4 p.m. close in Windhoek. The Ghana Stock Exchange
Composite Index retreated for a fourth day, slipping 0.1 percent
to 1,162.05 by the 3 p.m. close in Accra.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Crown Berger Ltd. (CRBG)  , a Kenyan paint maker and
retailer, advanced the most in almost three years, gaining 4
shillings, or 16 percent, to 29 shillings. The company reported
an 8 percent increase in first-half profit to 45.9 million
shillings ($490,000).  Rogers & Co. (ROGERS MP), Mauritius’s second-biggest
diversified company, rose the most in six months, gaining 5
rupees, or 1.8 percent, to 280 rupees. ENL Investment Ltd., a
Mauritius investment company, increased its stake in Rogers
after buying 5.2 percent of its traded shares, said Virginie
Corneillet, head of legal and corporate affairs of ENL Group.  Total Kenya Ltd. (TKNL KN),  Total SA (FP) ’s unit in the East
African nation, fell to its lowest in a week, dropping 50 cents,
or 2.3 percent, to 21.5 shillings. The company said profit in
the six months through June fell 74 percent after Kenya
introduced price controls in December.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Stephen Gunnion in Johannesburg at 
